8 Tips to Improve Digestion During Pregnancy: 
1️⃣ Move your body daily - even a little movement can help stimulate digestion🏃‍♀️
2️⃣slowly increase intake of fiber 🥦
3️⃣gradually increase intake of fermented foods, this helps to feed the good bugs in your gut
4️⃣avoid drinking too much liquid with meals - this can dilute your stomach acid too much making it harder for your stomach to break down food 
5️⃣ stay well hydrated, be sure to drink plenty of water between your meals💦
6️⃣add probiotic foods such as sweet potatoes 🍠
7️⃣ Add a good quality probiotic such as MegaSpore by Microbiome Labs
8️⃣ If dealing with constipation consider adding Magnesium Citrate and/or Vitamin C as Ascorbic Acid to assist bowel movements

Did you know that that digestion slows during pregnancy to help extract as much nutrition as possible!

April is C-Section Awareness Month. No matter how long it's been since your c-section, you can always work towards strengthening your deep core. Here are 5 exercises to try during your next workout!​​​​​​​​​
1️⃣ Pelvic tilts: make sure you're using your breathe to stimulate your pelvic floor and not just rolling your pelvic back and forth!
2️⃣ Hip rolls: build on your pelvic tilt for this move and just go as far as your body allows!
3️⃣ Mermaid stretch: this helps to open your hips, wake up your deep core muscles and helps to mobilize the tissue around your scar.
4️⃣ Swan press: focus here on keeping the movement small, because even the smallest movement can help awaken your core muscles.
5️⃣ Arch & rounds: this one is all about reaching out long and feeling the spreading between the sits bones.

5 Tips for Staying Active During Pregnancy 🤰🏼​​​​​​​​​
💥 Prioritize Your Movement Practice - if getting in movement is important to you, you'll make time for it in your day!

💥 Avoid Sitting for Too Long - set reminders on your phone to take a quick lap around the office or your house so you're not sitting for TOO long during the day.

💥 Add Exercises In Throughout Your Day - don't overthink it! Find pockets of your day where you can add in small movements, they add up!

💥 Bring Awareness to Your Posture - hard to do with a growing bump, but being aware of your posture is the foundation to all good fitness habits.

💥 Activate Your Pelvic Floor/Deep Core - with proper pelvic floor connection, you can have better back support, strengthen your deep core, and better your postpartum recovery.

Squats aren’t just for building your leg and glute muscles.

Did you know everything going on with your legs can affect your pelvic floor?

Here are some things to remember when doing squats for your pelvic floor:

✔️ Gently zip up from your pelvic floor & focus your energy up
✔️ Don’t tuck your pelvis under
✔️ Avoid over-arching your back
✔️ As you lower into your squat feel spreading at your sits-bones

When you're healing from childbirth, it's important to nourish your body with extra nutrients to help it heal and recover. Some foods you should consider eating more of during this time are:​​​​​​​​​

🍳  Protein-rich foods - protein is essential for healing and repairing tissues in the body. Good sources of protein include lean meats, fish, chicken, eggs, beans, nuts, and seeds.

🥬 Iron-rich foods - iron is important for replenishing blood loss after childbirth. Leafy green vegetables, lean red meat, and beans are good sources of iron.

🧀 Calcium-rich foods - calcium is important for bone health and can help prevent osteoporosis later in life. Good sources of calcium include dairy products and leafy greens.

🥑 Healthy fats - fats are important for hormone production and brain function. Good sources of healthy fats include avocados, nuts, seeds, and fatty fish.

🫘 Fiber-rich foods - constipation is common after childbirth, so eating plenty of fiber-rich foods can help. Whole grains, fruits, vegetables, and beans are all good sources of fiber.

🥣 Probiotics and fermented foods - including quality yogurts (dairy or non-dairy options), fermented foods such as sauerkraut and kimchi can all help to boost your gut microbiome which is a foundation for overall health.

In addition to these foods, it's important to stay hydrated by drinking plenty of water and other fluids. It's also a good idea to talk to your doctor or a registered dietitian for personalized recommendations based on your individual needs!

As your bump grows, your posture can shift, causing some aches + pains to creep in. To help you feel your best during pregnancy, here are some important postural tips to follow. First, walk in place & then stop…​​​​​​​​​
1️⃣ Did your feet land naturally under your hips? If not, what are your feet doing? You want to feel your weight evenly distributed throughout both feet.

2️⃣ Are you locking your knees? It’s common to do this during pregnancy as this is the body’s way of cheating & puts unnecessary tension & stress on your lower back. Start by softening your knees when you stand as this can help release your low back & allow you to connect through your pelvic floor & deep core more easily.

3️⃣ Avoid tucking your bum because it shuts off your pelvic floor & deep core and forces your back to do more work than it needs to. 

4️⃣ Are you rounding forward? To avoid doing this, focus on engaging your mid-back muscles. By lighting engaging your mid-back, you can use these muscles to hold up your neck & head, removing any tension.

Use these tips throughout your day! By lightly engaging your pelvic floor & deep core, you can move more easily, sleep better & prepare your body for labor, delivery & recovery postpartum. The biggest priority in those early postpartum weeks is to enjoy bonding with your baby & enjoy the down time.

The next is to listen to your body. If you’re ready for some activity, start slow. Getting outside, light walking & breath work can make you feel so much better in those early days!

As you focus on healing & movement, here are 3 areas to help wake up that deep core connection.

💥Posture - remember to lengthen tall through the top of your head & zip up your belly lightly. This will engage your pelvic floor!

💥Deep Core - always bring awareness to the muscles, especially while breathing. When held properly, you’ll feel al light core connection & be able to breathe deeply out to your sides & back.

💥Avoid Certain Exercises - it’s important to avoid exercises that put too much stress on your abdominals in early postpartum. This includes crunches, planks, or any exercise that causes “coning” of your belly.
